\fB\fIapplication_module() = Mod | [Mod | ExtraArgs] | #diameter_callback{}\fR\fR

.IP
.nf
Mod = atom()
ExtraArgs = list()

.fi

.PP
Module implementing the callback interface defined in \fIdiameter_app\fR, along with any extra arguments to be appended to those documented. Note that extra arguments specific to an outgoing request can be specified to \fIcall/4\fR, in which case those are appended to any module-specific extra arguments.

.PP
Specifying a \fI#diameter_callback{}\fR record allows individual functions to be configured in place of the usual \fIdiameter_app\fR callbacks. See \fIdiameter_callback.erl\fR for details.

.RE

application_opt()
.RS 2
Options defining a Diameter application. Has one of the following types.

{alias, application_alias()}
.RS 2
Unique identifier for the application in the scope of the service. Defaults to the value of the 
\fIdictionary\fR option.

.RE

{dictionary, atom()}
.RS 2
Name of an encode/decode module for the Diameter messages defined by the application. These modules are generated from files whose format is documented in diameter_dict(4).


.RE

{module, application_module()}
.RS 2
Callback module in which messages of the Diameter application are handled. See 
\fIdiameter_app\fR for the required interface and semantics.

.RE

{state, term()}
.RS 2
Initial callback state. The prevailing state is passed to some 
\fIdiameter_app\fR callbacks, which can then return a new state. Defaults to the value of the \fIalias\fR option.

.RE

{call_mutates_state, true|false}
.RS 2
Whether or not the pick_peer/4 application callback can modify the application state. Defaults to 
\fIfalse\fR.
.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRpick_peer/4 callbacks are serialized when this option is \fItrue\fR, which is a potential performance bottleneck. A simple Diameter client may suffer no ill effects from using mutable state but a server or agent that responds to incoming request should probably avoid it.



.RE

{answer_errors, callback|report|discard}
.RS 2
Manner in which incoming answer messages containing decode errors are handled.

.PP
If \fIcallback\fR then errors result in a handle_answer/4 callback in the same fashion as for handle_request/3, with errors communicated in the \fIerrors\fR field of the \fI#diameter_packet{}\fR passed to the callback. If \fIreport\fR then an answer containing errors is discarded without a callback and a warning report is written to the log. If \fIdiscard\fR then an answer containing errors is silently discarded without a callback. In both the \fIreport\fR and \fIdiscard\fR cases the return value for the \fIcall/4\fR invocation in question is as if a callback had taken place and returned \fI{error, failure}\fR.

.PP
Defaults to \fIdiscard\fR.


.RE

{request_errors, answer_3xxx|answer|callback}
.RS 2
Manner in which incoming requests are handled when an error other than 3007 (DIAMETER_APPLICATION_UNSUPPORTED, which cannot be associated with an application callback module), is detected.

.PP
If \fIanswer_3xxx\fR then requests are answered without a handle_request/3 callback taking place. If \fIanswer\fR then even 5xxx errors are answered without a callback unless the connection in question has configured the RFC 3588 common dictionary as noted below. If \fIcallback\fR then a handle_request/3 callback always takes place and its return value determines the answer sent to the peer, if any.

.PP
Defaults to \fIanswer_3xxx\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRAnswers sent by diameter set the E-bit in the Diameter Header. Since RFC 3588 allows only 3xxx result codes in an \fIanswer-message\fR, \fIanswer\fR has the same semantics as \fIanswer_3xxx\fR when the transport in question has been configured with \fIdiameter_gen_base_rfc3588\fR as its common dictionary. Since RFC 6733 allows both 3xxx and 5xxx result codes in an \fIanswer-message\fR, a transport with \fIdiameter_gen_base_rfc6733\fR as its common dictionary does distinguish between \fIanswer_3xxx\fR and \fIanswer\fR.



.RE


