peer_filter() = term()
.RS 2
Filter passed to 
\fIcall/4\fR in order to select candidate peers for a pick_peer/4 callback. Has one of the following types.
none
.RS 2
Matches any peer. This is a convenience that provides a filter equivalent to no filter.


.RE

host
.RS 2
Matches only those peers whose Origin-Host has the same value as Destination-Host in the outgoing request in question, or any peer if the request does not contain a Destination-Host AVP.


.RE

realm
.RS 2
Matches only those peers whose Origin-Realm has the same value as Destination-Realm in the outgoing request in question, or any peer if the request does not contain a Destination-Realm AVP.


.RE

{host, any|DiameterIdentity()}
.RS 2
Matches only those peers whose Origin-Host has the specified value, or all peers if the atom 
\fIany\fR.

.RE

{realm, any|DiameterIdentity()}
.RS 2
Matches only those peers whose Origin-Realm has the specified value, or all peers if the atom 
\fIany\fR.

.RE

{eval, eval()}
.RS 2
Matches only those peers for which the specified 
\fIeval()\fR returns \fItrue\fR when applied to the connection's \fIdiameter_caps\fR record. Any other return value or exception is equivalent to \fIfalse\fR.

.RE

{neg, peer_filter()}
.RS 2
Matches only those peers not matched by the specified filter.


.RE

{all, [peer_filter()]}
.RS 2
Matches only those peers matched by each filter in the specified list.


.RE

{any, [peer_filter()]}
.RS 2
Matches only those peers matched by at least one filter in the specified list. The resulting list will be in match order, peers matching the first filter of the list sorting before those matched by the second, and so on.


.RE

{first, [peer_filter()]}
.RS 2
Like 
\fIany\fR, but stops at the first filter for which there are matches, which can be much more efficient when there are many peers. For example, the following filter causes only peers best matching both the host and realm filters to be presented.
.IP
.nf
{first, [{all, [host, realm]}, realm]}

.fi


.RE

.PP
An invalid filter is equivalent to \fI{any,[]}\fR, a filter that matches no peer.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe \fIhost\fR and \fIrealm\fR filters cause the Destination-Host and Destination-Realm AVPs to be extracted from the outgoing request, assuming it to be a record- or list-valued \fIdiameter_codec:message()\fR, and assuming at most one of each AVP. If this is not the case then the \fI{host|realm, \fR\fIDiameterIdentity()\fR\fI}\fR filters must be used to achieve the desired result. An empty \fIDiameterIdentity()\fR (which should not be typical) matches all hosts/realms for the purposes of filtering.


.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRA \fIhost\fR filter is not typically desirable when setting Destination-Host since it will remove peer agents from the candidates list.



.RE

